data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11 (Cosmos provider), the **sync-over-async opt-in is removed entirely**. The configuration you had in .NET 10 (e.g., `AllowSynchronousIO = true` on the Cosmos options) no longer exists. All four of your synchronous calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:

| Method | Throws | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `ToList()` | ✅ | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | ✅ | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | ✅ | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | ✅ | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

## Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key actions:**
1. Remove the `AllowSynchronousIO` / sync-over-async opt-in from your Cosmos DB configuration — it won't compile.
2. Convert all repository methods to `async Task<T>` and use the `*Async()` LINQ/DbContext equivalents.
3. Propagate `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.).
